Query1.Notes:
There are almost as many recipes for Swedish meatballs as there are Swedish amateur chefs. The three main types are: (1) small, fried, served without sauce; 
(2) large, fried, served in brown gravy; 
(3) medium size, boiled, served in sauce. 
The present recipe is a very simple version of type-1 meatballs, a childrens favourite.

Query1.Instructions:
Combine oil, lemon juice, chopped onion, garlic, bay leaves, oregano and black pepper. Add lamb; stir to coat. Cover and refrigerate for at least 4 hours, stirring several times. Remove meat, reserving marinade. Thread meat, red onion, bell pepper and mushrooms on skewers. Preheat broiler; place shish kebabs on rack in pan, about 3 inches from heat. Broil, turning and basting occasionally with marinade, until meat and vegetables are well browned but meat is still pink in center, 10 to 15 minutes total.

Per serving: 
Calories 341; 
Protein 46g, 54%; 
Carbohydrates 10g, 12%; 
Fat 13g, 34%; 
Sodium 122mg.

~- Mix the sugar with the tuong and water. Add some slices of the red chili pepper. Sprinkle with roasted peanuts. 
~- Side notes: ) Roasted peanuts - Add 1/2 cup of shelled peanuts to a very hot wok and stir until the skins turn black and scorched. Transfer to a colander and cool (2-3 min). Wipe off skins. 
) Tuong - Sometimes labeled "Vietnamese Soy Sauce" in the U.S. but it is actually quite different from "regular" soy sauce.
